Motivation

The Department of Housing and Community Development in Emil City wants to improve their outreach strategy for a home repair tax credit program by using data-driven approaches to identify eligible homeowners, predict their likelihood of participating in a home repair tax credit program, and assess the cost-effectiveness of their outreach efforts. The ultimate aim is to increase the number of participants while reducing the money spent on marketing.

Goals:

  • Increase Credit Uptake: They want more eligible homeowners to take advantage of the home repair tax credit program. In other words, they aim to boost the number of people who use this benefit.

  • Decrease Marketing Expenditure: They want to reduce the amount of money spent on marketing efforts. This implies that they want to make their outreach more efficient and cost-effective.

Methodology:

  • Build a Classification Model: This model will use a sample of data from previous outreach campaigns to predict whether a homeowner is likely to enter the tax credit program or not. It will sort homeowners into two categories: those likely to participate and those unlikely to participate.

  • Cost/Benefit Analysis: This involves evaluating the financial costs associated with their outreach efforts (marketing and other resources) against the benefits gained by having more homeowners enter the program. The goal is to determine the effectiveness of the outreach and to allocate the limited resources more strategically.

Data Exploration

Key Variables

Inflation Rate (inflation_rate): When the US inflation rate is high, the likelihood of the outcome being no is notable. This suggests a negative correlation between a high inflation rate and program participation.

Number of Previous Contacts (previous): When the number of times a person was previously contacted (previous) is high, the likelihood of the outcome being yes is more prominent. This implies a positive correlation between a higher number of previous contacts and a greater chance of program participation.

Unemployment Rate on the Day of Contact (unemploy_rate): When the rate of unemployment on the day of contact is low (or even negative), the likelihood of the outcome being yes is significant. This indicates that a lower unemployment rate is associated with a higher likelihood of program participation.

Modeling

In a logistic regression model, were trying to predict a binary outcome, like whether the homeowner will take the subsidy (1) or not (0). The model calculates coefficients for independent variables, which represent the change in the probability of the outcome based on changes in those variables.

We partition our data into a 65/35 split for training and testing, it means that we use 65% of the data to train the model and 35% to test its performance. By using a 65/35 split instead of a balanced 50/50 split, we ensure that the model has a more appropriate balance of examples for each outcome class. This can help the model perform better because its exposed to more examples of the majority class (no) and can still learn from the minority class (yes) as well.

Kitchen Sink Model

The McFaddens number for the kitchen sink is 0.2450601, meaning that this model explains about 24.5% of the variance in the model.

Feature Engineered Model

In the feature engineering process, changes were made to the dataset with the aim of potentially improving the models performance. The following variables were transformed based on the results of the Data Exploration.

Education: Grouped education levels into categories to simplify and make them more interpretable. basic.4y, basic.6y, and basic.9y were categorized as elem (elementary education), high.school and professional.course as high, and university.degree as advanced. Illiterate and unknown were both categorized as basic.

Job: Re-categorized jobs by grouping retired and student into a non-working category. All other jobs were categorized as working. This simplification aimed to reduce the number of categories and potentially improve model performance as the frequency of positive outcomes was high for retired.

Month: Grouped months into low freq (April, March, September, October, November, December) and high freq (May, June, July, August) based on their occurrence. This grouping helps capture potential seasonality in the data, which may be relevant for the models predictions.

Pdays: Redefined the pdays variable to categorize it into recent for values 0-6, 1-2 weeks for values 7-14, and more than 2 weeks for values 15-21. The value 999 was categorized as NA.

After these transformations, I split the data into training and testing sets and built a logistic regression model (glm) to predict the target variable y_numeric using all the engineered features and assessed its performance.

The McFaddens number for the kitchen sink is 0.2215975, meaning that this model explains about 22.1% of the variance in the model. This means that our model is not improving as we expected it to.

Cross-Validations: ROC, Sensitivity, Specificity

In both models;

ROC: Both models exhibit similar ROC values, indicating that they have good discrimination ability in distinguishing between participants and non-participants.

Sensitivity: The Kitchen Sink model has slightly higher sensitivity, suggesting it performs slightly better in identifying participants. However, the Engineered model still maintains a reasonable sensitivity.

Specificity: The Engineered model shows a significantly higher specificity, implying it performs better in correctly identifying non-participants, making it more efficient in reducing marketing costs.

Comparing the models, the Engineered model appears to be lightly more suitable for the Departments goal of decreasing marketing expenditure while still maintaining a good ROC. It achieves a marginally higher specificity, which helps in targeting marketing efforts more efficiently. However, its important to consider the specific cost-benefit analysis and financial goals of the outreach efforts to make an informed decision about model selection.

Kitchen Sink

ROC: Area Under Curve

The AUC (Area Under the Curve) quantifies the models ability to distinguish between the two classes, typically the positive and negative classes. In our model the AUC is 0.761 which indicates that the model is better than random chance. It means that, on average, the model is able to correctly rank a randomly chosen positive instance higher than a randomly chosen negative instance in about 76.1% of cases.

The closer the AUC value is to 1, the better the models discriminative ability. An AUC of 0.761 suggests a moderate level of discrimination. While not perfect, it indicates that the model has some capability to distinguish between the two classes.

Cost/Benefit Analysis

The cost-benefit analysis is a detailed breakdown of the financial implications of different outcomes in the context of a logistic model that predicts homeowner enrollment in a subsidy program. The analysis primarily focuses on the financial implications of true positives, true negatives, false positives, and false negatives.

  1. True Positives: These are the cases where the model correctly predicted that a property owner would enroll in the subsidy program.

    • Revenue: $248,000

    • For these homeowners, the model successfully predicted their enrollment, and marketing resources were allocated. The net benefit was calculated by considering that 25% of homeowners who took the credit generated a net benefit of $12,400 per homeowner, accounting for the costs of marketing resources and the credit itself.

  2. True Negatives: These are cases where the model correctly predicted that a homeowner would not enroll, and no marketing resources were allocated.

    • Revenue: $0

    • In these cases, the model correctly predicted that the homeowner would not take the credit, and no marketing expenses were incurred.

  3. False Positives: These are cases where the model incorrectly predicted that a homeowner would take the credit, and marketing resources were allocated.

    • Revenue: -$48,450

    • In these cases, the model incorrectly predicted that homeowners would take the credit, leading to the allocation of marketing resources. However, no credit was allocated, resulting in a cost of $2,850 per homeowner (which includes staff and resources). This cost was incurred, but no revenue was generated.

  4. False Negatives: These are cases where the model predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit, but they did.

    • Revenue: $0

    • These homeowners took the credit for reasons unrelated to the marketing campaign, and the analysis assumes that the cost/benefit of this is $0.

cost_benefit_table <-
   testProbs %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
       gather(Variable, Count) %>%
       mutate(Revenue =
               case_when(Variable == "True_Negative"  ~ Count * 0,
                         Variable == "True_Positive"  ~ (12400 * Count),

              "We predicted correctly homeowner would not take the credit, no marketing resources were allocated.",
              "We predicted correctly homeowner would enter credit program; allocated the marketing resource.",
              "We predicted that a homeowner would not take the credit but they did.",

Confusion Metric

The focus is on minimizing false positive expenditures to increase the efficacy of the subsidy program. The dollars spent on marketing represent a significant cost, and reducing false positives can reallocate resources toward subsidies for property owners. The analysis demonstrates the financial implications of different prediction outcomes based on the threshold chosen for the logistic model. In this specific analysis, a threshold of 0.5 was used.

The overall goal is to choose a threshold that maximizes the social benefit while minimizing marketing expenses. The analysis provides a quantitative understanding of the trade-offs involved in allocating resources for marketing and subsidies based on the models predictions. By choosing the right threshold, the Department can aim to maximize its social impact while managing costs effectively.

Here, we find that our optimal threshold is 0.18.

iterateThresholds <- function(data) {
  x = .01
  all_prediction <- data.frame()
  while (x <= 1) {
  
  this_prediction <-
      testProbs %>%
      mutate(predOutcome = ifelse(Probs > x, 1, 0)) %>%
      count(predOutcome, Outcome) %>%
      summarize(True_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==0]),
                True_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Negative = sum(n[predOutcome==0 & Outcome==1]),
                False_Positive = sum(n[predOutcome==1 & Outcome==0])) %>%
     gather(Variable, Count) %>%
   mutate(Revenue =
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Negative", Count * 0,
               ifelse(Variable == "True_Positive", 12400 * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Negative", 0 * Count,
               ifelse(Variable == "False_Positive", (-2850) * Count, 0)))),
            Threshold = x)
  
  all_prediction <- rbind(all_prediction, this_prediction)
  x <- x + .01
  }
return(all_prediction)
}

whichThreshold <- iterateThresholds(testProbs2)

Optimal Threshold vs 50% Threshold

  1. Threshold 0.18:

    • Total Revenue: $690,750

    • Interpretation: When using a threshold of 0.18 for the logistic model, the total revenue generated is $690,750. This means that the model predicts a certain number of homeowners to enroll in the subsidy program based on this threshold. The revenue includes both correctly predicted enrollments (true positives) and any associated costs or benefits related to marketing and subsidies. This level of revenue is achieved by making predictions that include a relatively broader range of potential enrollees, which may lead to more enrollments.

  2. Threshold 0.5:

    • Total Revenue: $199,550

    • Interpretation: When using a threshold of 0.5 for the logistic model, the total revenue generated is $199,550. This threshold represents a different level of model stringency, where only predictions with higher confidence are considered. Consequently, the model is less likely to predict enrollments, which reduces the total revenue. While this threshold may reduce the revenue, it could also lead to cost savings by reducing false positive predictions and the associated marketing costs.

The choice of threshold is a trade-off between maximizing revenue and minimizing costs. A lower threshold captures more potential enrollees but may also lead to more false positives, increasing marketing costs. In contrast, a higher threshold reduces false positives but may miss out on some potential enrollees, potentially reducing revenue. The optimal threshold depends on the organizations goals and the balance they aim to strike between revenue generation and cost control.

Conclusion

In considering the goodness of fit of the model and its potential impact on revenue, it is evident that the imbalanced dataset poses a significant challenge. The current model may be heavily skewed towards homeowners who did not enter the program, as indicated by the low sensitivity.

A balanced sample that adequately represents both classes could lead to more accurate model results. While the models specificity is high, its ability to identify homeowners who would enroll in the subsidy program requires more work.

Recommendation:

In its current state, I would not recommend putting this model into production. The imbalanced dataset and the low sensitivity of the model pose substantial limitations. To consider production, the following steps are essential:

  1. Improved Sampling Techniques: Utilize better sampling techniques, rather than relying on random samples of previous campaigns, to ensure a balanced representation of both classes in the dataset.

  2. Model Enhancement: Refine the model to improve its ability to identify positive cases, focusing on a more targeted audience using classification techniques.

  3. Enhanced Marketing Efforts: Allocate additional resources to working sessions for program application processes, catering to eligible homeowners to ensure that marketing materials yield a better response rate.

Balancing the dataset and refining the model are critical steps for making this predictive tool a valuable asset for increasing homeowner enrollment in the subsidy program. Without these enhancements, the model may not reach its full potential in a production environment.
